The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Malaysia spices up telecom deal dossier

 OUR CORRESPONDENT

 New Delhi, March 10: Telekom Malaysia (TM) today picked up a 49 per cent stake in Spice Telecom for Rs 805 crore ($178.85 million), marking the entry of Malaysias largest telecom operator into the country.

 This is the third telecom deal on the trot. The deal drill was kicked off on Wednesday when Singapores Temasek bought a 9.9 per cent stake in Tata Teleservices and was followed up by Sterling infotech, which picked up an 8 per cent stake in the same company.

 TMs international investment holding company ? TM International Sdn Bhd (TMI) ? bought the stake from Deutsche Bank and Ashmore Investment Management Limited consortium (DBA). 

 The remaining 51 per cent in Spice remains with the existing shareholders ? the B.K. Modi-promoted Mcorp Global Ltd and its associates. 

 Lazard India was the financial adviser to the transaction. 

 A statement jointly released in Kuala Lumpur and New Delhi said, The definitive agreements governing the transaction were executed in Kuala Lumpur today. 

 The completion of the transaction is expected within a month, subject to regulatory approvals.

 Spice is a privately held company, providing cellular telecom services in Punjab and Karnataka. The company is also close to obtaining licences for six new circles ? Jammu amp; Kashmir, Haryana, Rajasthan, Himachal Pradesh, Uttar Pradesh West/ East) ? as well as national long distance (NLD) and international long distance (ILD) licences. 




